T1  - Subclinical cardiovascular disease and polycystic ovary syndrome.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.fertnstert.2022.02.028
A1  - Gomez, Joanne Michelle D
A1  - VanHise, Katherine
A1  - Stachenfeld, Nina
A1  - Chan, Jessica L
A1  - Merz, Noel Bairey
A1  - Shufelt, Chrisandra
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) impacts approximately 6%-10% of women worldwide, with hallmark features of hyperandrogenism, irregular menses, infertility, and polycystic appearing ovaries on ultrasound. In addition, PCOS is associated with several endocrine and metabolic disorders, including obesity, insulin resistance and diabetes mellitus, hypertension, dyslipidemia and metabolic syndrome, which all increase the risk for subclinical cardiovascular disease (CVD), the presence of altered vascular endothelium without overt CVD. In this review, we summarize the most recent literature regarding subclinical CVD in women with PCOS, including markers such as flow-mediated dilation, arterial stiffness, coronary artery calcium scores, carotid intima-media thickness and visceral and epicardial fat. Copyright © 2022 American Society for Reproductive Medicine. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
