ID  - 30798906
T1  - Urinary volatile metabolomics as a viable alternative diagnostic tool for polycystic ovary syndrome: An exploratory hypothesis.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.mehy.2019.02.009
A1  - Sankarganesh, Devaraj
A1  - Suriyakalaa, Udhayaraj
A1  - Ramachandran, Rajamanickam
A1  - Achiraman, Shanmugam
A1  - Arunachalam, Sankarganesh
A1  - Angayarkanni, Jayaraman
Y1  - 2019//
Y2  - 20190202//
N2  - Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) is a metabolic disorder prevalent globally. Female infertility cases are also on the increase during the recent times which almost matches with the increasing incidence of PCOS. The NIH-USA-defined symptoms for clinical confirmation of PCOS include oligo-ovulation, elevated androgen level and presence of cysts in the ovary. Therapeutic approaches to PCOS require confirmatory diagnostics such as measurement of hormones and ultrasound scan of the ovary, which are in part, invasive. Conversely, the volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that are present in body fluids (urine, feces, saliva, etc.) and exhaled breath are reported to be endogenously altered in diseased state, which may be indicative of diseases including cancer. We hypothesize that the hindered metabolic state in PCOS condition would conditionally alter the VOCs that eventually are excreted in urine, which may offer a template to develop a viable and non-invasive diagnostic tool. Copyright © 2019 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
